<h1 class="heading">
    Get started
</h1>
<p>Import the latest paclet from GitHub</p>
<div class="example">
    <code class="language-mathematica" style="margin-left: 0;">
    PacletInstall["https://github.com/JerryI/tinyweb-mathematica/blob/main/Tinyweb.paclet?raw=true"]
    &lt;&lt;Tinyweb`
    </code>
</div>
<p>Create the initial structure of the project</p>
<div class="example">
    <code class="language-mathematica" style="margin-left: 0;">
        -- &nbsp; your_project.nb<br>
        -- &nbsp; public/<br>
        -- &nbsp; -- &nbsp; index.wsp
    </code>
</div>

<p>To create the simplest server - use function</p>
<div class="example">
    <code class="language-mathematica" style="margin-left: 0;">
        server = WEBServer[&quot;addr&quot; -&gt; &quot;127.0.0.1:80&quot;, <br />
        &quot;path&quot; -&gt; NotebookDirectory[] &lt;&gt; &quot;public&quot;, &quot;socket-close&quot; -&gt; True] <br />
        <br />
        server // WEBServerStart
    </code>
</div>

<p>Note: the parameter "socket-close" stands for the behavior when the response was sent. True means it will be closed, False - it will be collected to the garbage and after a few iterations will be closed. It can prevent connection issues on some Windows machines, because of a bug in TCP library. The connection closes before the whole data has sent.</p>

<p>Stop the server</p>
<div class="example">
    <code class="language-mathematica" style="margin-left: 0;">
        server // WEBServerStop
    </code>
</div>

